= Expansion of Public Works

With the abolishment of reparations at Lausanne, the Brüning cabinet finally feels comfortable to expand funding for its recently enacted public works program. A billion dollars in bonds released by the government is used to fund the program, and money begins to flow in the economy again.

This marks a real turning point, and along with the abolishment of reparations, the radicalizing effects of sky-high unemployment and the Versailles Treaty are diminished. The set of conditions that have enabled the <span style="color: #7A3C00;">Nazis</span>'s meteoric rise begins to unravel, depriving them of the fuel that once drove their ascent.

